What is SQL?

SQL (Structured Query Language) is the standard language used to interact with relational databases.

Key Facts About SQL:

• CRUD Operations – lets you Create, Read, Update, and Delete data with simple, declarative commands

• Cross-Compatible – works with many database engines (SQLite, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and SQL Server)

• Declarative Syntax – you describe what you want, not how to get it

• Powerful Queries – supports joins, filters, aggregations, and subqueries for advanced data manipulation

• Backend Essential – widely used in APIs, web apps, and server-side logic

• Production-Ready – powers dashboards, reporting tools, and scalable enterprise systems

++++++++++++++++
What are SQLite, MySQL, PostgreSQL?

These are database engines, software systems that store, manage, and retrieve data using SQL.

DBMS (Database Management System)

Database Engine | Description | Uses SQL? | Common Use Cases

SQLite | Lightweight, file-based database. No server needed. | Yes | Mobile apps, prototypes, small projects

MySQL | Popular open-source client-server database. Fast and widely supported. | Yes | Web applications, CMS platforms (e.g., WordPress)

PostgreSQL | Advanced, open-source database with powerful features. | Yes | APIs, enterprise systems, data analytics


+++++++++++++++++++++
CRUD Operations in SQL

CRUD stands for:

Operation | SQL Command | Description

Create | INSERT INTO | Adds new records
(API equivalent: POST)

Read | SELECT | Retrieves data
(API equivalent: GET)

Update | UPDATE | Modifies existing records
(API equivalent: PUT)

Delete | DELETE FROM | Removes records
(API equivalent: DELETE)

Example Table (Database Table)

Table name: coupons

Columns:
-id
-discount
-name

Key SQL commands include:

SQL Syntax | Purpose

SELECT column FROM table | Fetch data

WHERE | Filter results

ORDER BY | Sort results

LIMIT | Restrict number of rows

INSERT INTO, UPDATE, DELETE | Modify data


+++++++++++++++
Real-World Use Cases

Common Use Cases for Relational Databases

• Login systems and user authentication

• Inventory and product management

• Analytics dashboards and reports

• APIs that serve structured data

Relational databases are widely used in:

• Web development

• Data science

• Enterprise systems
