cursor.execute(""" https://blog.paulcoding.com/posts/sqlite3-cheatsheet/ or [w3 scool](https://blog.paulcoding.com/posts/sqlite3-cheatsheet/)s
  CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS users (  # 'users is the table name'/ You use CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS so the 
  database does not give an error if the table is already there. When the program runs, 
  the database first checks if the users table exists. If it does not exist, it creates the table. 
  If it already exists, the database simply does nothing and the program continues running normally. 
  This makes the program safe to run multiple times without crashing.

    -
    -- It means the database will automatically number every row.
    -- id = name of the column
    -- INTEGER = stores numbers
    -- PRIMARY KEY = unique ID for each row
    -- AUTOINCREMENT = automatically adds 1 for every new row
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,

    username TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,
    password TEXT NOT NULL
  )
""")


title TEXT
This column stores the title of the record as text. It can contain words or letters.

description TEXT NOT NULL
This column stores a description as text. NOT NULL means it cannot be empty.

amount INT NOT NULL
This column stores a number (like money or quantity). INT means integer. NOT NULL means a value is required.

date TEXT NOT NULL
This column stores the date as text (for example "2026-03-11"). It cannot be empty.

category TEXT NOT NULL
This column stores the category name as text (like "food", "rent", "transport"). It must have a value.


 "INSERT INTO users (username, password) VALUES (?, ?)"
 INSERT INTO users → add a new row to the "users" table
 (username, password) → the columns where the data will go
 VALUES (?, ?) → placeholders for the values that will be inserted

 (username, password)
 these are the actual values that replace the ? placeholders
 example: if username="leo" and password="1234"
 the database will insert ("leo", "1234") into the users table

